If you're curious about oracle card readings in general this will be a sweet little introduction to the practice. If you're already familiar with oracle cards, or already do your own readings, this could be a fun way to maybe get to know some new, unusual, or less common decks! Please arrive shortly before the readings start to add your name to the signup sheet & grab a time slot.

column19: This three part series is great for any skill level! Take all three or choose the ones that best suit your needs. Isolation Initiation is for new hoopers looking to start their isolation journey. We will cover all basic isolation techniques including one handed, two handed, ghosting, and cat eye isolations. Isolation Exploration is for intermediate hoopers who would like to expand upon the knowledge they already have or learned in part one of the series. In this class we will take our isolations to the next level with plane changes, breaks, transitions and much more. Isolation Combination is for advanced isolators or those who have taken parts one and two of the series. We will cover predesigned combos and learn how to cultivate this creative process in our private practices.

column19: The Fire Safety Meeting is a requirement for all breathers who would like to spin fire and/or volunteer for the fire circle on any given night of the festival. There will be one meeting each evening to ensure everyone has an opportunity to attend. You WILL NOT be allowed to spin fire or volunteer without taking the safety course. NO EXCEPTIONS, thank you! During this meeting we will cover all of the fire safety rules and Breathe procedures in place to keep performers, volunteers, and spectators safe. Attendees will be given a crash course regarding regarding how to dress fire-safe, prop maintenance, our fuel depot and circle protocol, active safety, spinning fire, how to safely extinguish props, and emergency situations. Once completed, breathers will be given a wrist band to prove they have taken the course. You must wear your wristband to the circle at night in order to spin. We look forward to cultivating a safe space for fire artists to play and entertain at Breathe.

column19: Whether you have just begun your handstand practice or have been at it for years there are always techniques and exercises that can help you find a few more seconds or maybe even a few more minutes of float! Your instructor brings techniques from traditional gymnastics, martial arts, yoga and high-level circus. We will explore stretches, strengthening and alignment exercises, partner work and of course play in our free and spotted handstands and other handbalancing shapes! No handstand experience is required but it is suggested that you feel comfortable kicking into a handstand with a spotter to get the most out of the workshop.

column19: The Tao that can be spoken is not the eternal Tao. And so rather than speak about it, we're just going to laugh about it. Laughing deeper and deeper into who we are, allowing our laughter to shake loose those stagnant parts of our being and awaken the life within. Cultivating through this practice, not only an inner smile, but also a deep inner laughter, that we can carry with us everywhere we go, as we move through life with a new sense of lightness.

column19: An introduction to the craft of improvisation through the lens of meditation. Participants will be guided through a meditation designed to enhance group mind, which in improvisation is the sense that no one is leading and no one is following but acting as one cohesive whole. We will then run through some simple and fun improv exercises that explore group mind and make it more tangible and real. The workshop will culminate in a short improv jam where put together everything we've learned and create comedic scenes on the spot.

column19: Dreams are deeply entrenched into our everyday lives, regardless of our consciousness of them. We spend nearly 1/3 of our lives asleep. We can use this time for healing, wish fulfillment, spiritual growth, creativity, and more. Whether you're looking to kick start or deepen your dreaming practice, in this workshop we will take a deeper look at our dreams and how to make the most of them, learn about Myths and History of Dreams, the Science of Sleep and Dreams, How to Improve Your Sleep, Dream Interpretation, Lucid Dreaming, Dealing With Nightmares and Sleep Paralysis, and the ancient practice of Tibetan Dream Yoga. This workshop will enhance your relationship with your dream life and shed light into the darkness we find in the night to Discover The Dreamer within you. Please bring a dream journal and something to write with.

column19: A Death Café is a group-directed discussion to practice the art of talking openly about our own mortality so as to make the most of our finite lives. Participants will have the opportunity to share their own, and listen to, a myriad of different views on death and dying using question cards as conversation starters. Anyone of any age, background, spiritual belief (or lack thereof!) is welcome to attend as the results are enriched by the variety of participants. Let's break the taboo, together!

column18: Presence Practice: Improv for Higher Consciousness
column19: The key to connected work is staying in the present moment. If the actor/improviser experiences a personal trigger during their work it kicks them out of the present moment and into the mind. This creates a disconnected performance. I developed a technique called Presence Practice. This improv/acting technique combines kundalini yoga, breath-work, and subtle energy body activations with classic acting and improv exercises designed to hold you in the present moment. When the actor/improviser can identify when they are in or out of the present moment, they take their craft to the next level. This workshop is designed to both illuminate and remove the emotional and physical blocks that hold you out of your presence and you will learn to hold the frequency of presence for longer periods of time, much like meditation. Come practice improv consciously, raise your vibration, and be a part of the funniest, most authentic improv once can experience in non-linear time and space. This workshop is designed for actors, improvisers or anyone seeking presence.

column18: All about polymers: Nerd out with a material scientist turned molecular biologist
column19: Polymers are the ultimate man-made materials. They are used to make all kinds of things from airplanes and water bottles to -- you guessed it -- slacklines. They can be stiff or stretchy, stronger than steel or utterly disposable, absorbent or waterproof. Some can be recycled while others decompose and most do neither. How? Why? We will learn about what polymers are, how the biological ones (DNA, proteins) make up the building blocks of life, and how man-made ones are related to them. We will talk about common synthetic polymers such as polyethylene, nylon, polyester etc., their macro properties, and how these properties relate to their basic molecular structures.

column19: Contact improv focuses on free and safe movement, either on your own or more often with others. It teaches individuals to listen using all parts of the body, paying attention to where the body is in contact with something or someone else. It is about exploring how bodies can fit into one another and move fluidly with each other using weight sharing, gravity, momentum other natural elements. It's like a flow art with the human body as a prop. Often it involves falling to the ground softly, rolling around there, and getting up again with others in infinite many patterns. It's not about what the dance looks like, but how it feels. Come explore some tools for improvisation and then transition into free play/jam!

column18: The Universe Beads / a mala for the modern era
column19: We will assemble pocket universes, strings of beads representing the 13.8 billion year history of life, the solar system, and the cosmos at large. Bead by bead, 25 million years at a time, we will recreate the history of everything in our minds. Special symbolic beads represent individual events in this epic, like the ignition of the first stars, the formation of molten earth, and the first forays of life onto land. Together, the beads form a wearable timeline, a tactile teaching aid to be shared and admired as we boldly advance the vanguard of reality. Beads, string, and instruction will be provided by Rain.

column18: Letting Go of Perfectionism and Form in Yoga
column19: What if I told you your body is perfect? What happens when what we feel in poses is more important than how we look? Have your mind blown and never see poses the same way again in 90 minutes or less. Using both actual anatomical images and living breathing examples drawn from our group we will empower you to move beyond aesthetic concerns and towards a functional approach. Learn to discriminate between what we can change and what just is, and embrace the realities of skeletal variation to free you from goal-oriented yoga.

column19: Metta is a Pali word that translates to benevolence, loving-kindness, friendliness, amity, good will, and active interest in others. Take some time in your day to intentionally cultivate and radiate loving-kindness. Metta meditation involves first focusing the mind. Then, we will cultivate love and well wishes for ourselves, followed by an expansion to people you love, people who are neutral to you, people who you have difficulty with, and ultimately to all beings everywhere. This is a simple but profound practice! Transform your energy, transform the world! Caution: May cause feelings of intense happiness, openness, and connection with others!

column19: Hellth can be understood as a place that we all frequently visit, but rarely want to stay. It is a place where we understand that something awful is happening to us, but for our benefit. Hellth is a workshop dedicated to processing the yoga of suffering, finding union in pain and sacredness in mental illness. Aaron will create a space for us all to congregate, and will hazily guide us through his experiences with drug addiction, self harm, psychosis, psych wards, enlightenment, general sadness, and through his successes and failures with practices that draw on alchemy, astrology, creativity, magic, and just sticking with it. There may be questions, there may be answers, there may just be a feeling that you should have gone to a different workshop. Ultimately, we will learn the power of the mind in working with gratitude, and how in hell, we can avoid arguing with whoever gives us a glass of water.

column18: Exploring Time & Space: An Intro to Poi Spinning
column19: This workshop will guide the participants through the basics of Poi spinning. The key focus will be on time and space. In other words, we will use the grid theory to cover different planes in space used when spinning poi, the different directions used, and the different timing used when spinning poi. From here, we will be able to unveil the different combinations in which all of these factors come together to produce a flow state of being with the Poi. This workshop is intended for completely new and beginner level poi spinners to explore Poi in a safe and welcoming environment. It will teach the participants that anyone can spin poi and it can be a very beneficial practice for mental, emotional, and physical health. We will learn that flow in its essence is the combination of discipline and surrender: a valuable life lesson in itself. Bringing your own poi is recommended; however if you are unable to bring your own, there will be extra practice poi available for use.

column19: This workshop has been prepared by Breathers looking to be inclusive of members of marginalized and oppressed groups attending Breathe. This is what we have learned so far and is by no means a doctrine or set of requirements. We are looking to share our education so far about the experience of people whose existence in western culture has been riddled with suffering due to societal expectations, subconscious narratives, and systemic bias. We will share basic principles of inclusion, as well as Active Listening Skills used by clinicians, therapists, mediators, and other professional positions who practice validation and empathy. It is our hope that this workshop will help you to feel more equipped to hold gentile, loving, empowering, and supportive spaces for other people to verbally process their experiences. *Note, this workshop is a requirement if you'd like to volunteer in the Diversity Tent.

column19: This is an open discussion on living along side nature and not against what is natural. We will cover land development, alternative structures, sustainable materials, and how to use the Earth's natural cycles to our advantage. I often ask myself, "If we are the most intelligent and/or conscious species on the planet then why are we the only ones that pay to live here?"

column18: Intro to Music, Music Performance, and Music Tech
column19: This class will cover a basic introduction to all things music and music performance. You'll receive a basic introduction to music theory, basic sound gear set-up for amplified performances with hands on learning, professional stage presence techniques, and finish with a question session for all aspiring musicians, performers, or sound technicians. This workshop is led by Veronika Nelson, Breathe's Music Harmony Director. Her experience includes studying Musical Theatre at the conservatory level, performing Off-Broadway, and working with professional bands in NYC, Denver, and internationally. Veronika has taught in professional spaces all over the United States.

column18: Breathe Family Song Circle for All Ages!
column19: Come have a playful musical adventure with your Breathe family! This workshop aims to nurture all the roles we can play in our community - mother, brother, sister, grandfather, friend - while sharing song and dance! We will sing nature and traveling songs in circle-style. Parents and children (even the littlest of the little!) are highly encouraged to attend. We want to see the youngest and the oldest Breathe attendee at this workshop! Come play with child-safe musical instruments, scarves, bubbles, animal puppets, and sing about our beautiful Mother Earth and all the things that live here with us.

We will weave stories of people that illustrate the challenges and how they addressed them through developing skills and capacities like presence, authentic relating, self-compassion, reframing, support systems, in order to develop resilient relationships. Lastly, will practice aunthentic relating games that help us foster curiosity and self-awareness.

column18: Wahe Little Gurus: A Kids' Kundalini Experience
column19: Wahe Guru means "wonderful teacher." Our children can be our most wonderful teachers! I know mine have been! Join us for Wahe Little Gurus, a kid' Kundalini Yoga class. We will tune in to ourselves, practice some fun breathing and movements that originate from ancient Kundalini kriyas as taught by Yogi Bhajan. Kids will learn how to ground themselves, listen to their inner wisdom, breathe and flow through a yoga sequence that will leave them lighter, happier, and more balanced!

column18: The Art of Connection - A Partner Tantra Practice
column19: Connection is one of the most important things in our life, many of us have fear and/or do not know how to deeply connect to another person. So how do we create deeper connections to the people that we love? Join Brian and Emily as they guide you through a partner Tantra practice. Learn Tantra techniques to build and increase connection, vulnerability, trust and intimacy. This is a non-sexual partner practice, however we will discuss Tantra sacred sexuality and how to incorporate Tantric sexual practice with your partner into your practice. You do not need a partner to attend, you can come to watch and learn or partner with someone there that you feel comfortable partnering with. Please bring yoga mats, blankets, pillows, flowers, crystals etc. to create the sacred space where you will practice.

column18: Yoga for PTSD, Sexual Abuse and Trauma
column19: At some point in our lives each of us will experience some sort of trauma and some of us experience more traumas then others. These traumas can negatively change and affect us and those around us our entire lives especially if we do not deal with them. Join US Army Combat Veteran and Master Yoga Teacher Brian Coones as he talks about his journey of sexual abuse as a child, the traumas he experienced while serving in the Army and in Iraq and the practices that have helped him heal and ultimately saved his life. Brian has over 2500hr of education and over 5000hrs of teaching experience in 23 countries. He has worked with directly with hundreds of service members, veterans, victims of trauma and sexual abuse. Learn how you can use these practices to help heal yourself as well as how to get involved and help others.

column19: The West African djembe drum dates back to the 13th century in the great Malian Empire of West Africa. Its origins and purpose in its traditional context are inextricably tied to supporting many aspects of village life (farming, ceremonies, celebrations, social groups, etc). Outside of West Africa, it is used recreationally by millions of people who play outside of the traditional way. I came up in non-tradition, then traditional djembe found me; I have a deep reverence for both and I see the need for instruction in both. In essence, djembe is about service; to a circumstance, person, event, idea, etc. In this workshop, we will cover djembe technique (so you get the most out of the instrument), a traditional rhythm, and how to be effective and intentional in a non-traditional setting with your djembe. The workshop will be taught on djembe and dunun drums. .......... Folks should bring their djembe or dunun drums if they have them.

column19: Imagine this scene: you are lying down in a room, in savasana (in Yoga they call it corpse pose; lying on your back in total relaxation). You are surrounded by other people lying about, all heads pointed toward Taylor. As he gives basic instructions, sets expectations with you and guides you into a relaxed state, the instruments (drums, bells, shakers, flute, voice(s), etc) create a sonic backdrop which will be the magic carpet which will help transport you, while Taylor channels the ancestors. You decide how deep you go; you decide where you go and why; you decide what to do with your experience. Few leave the DRUMeditationª experience untouched; most leave it profoundly moved.

column19: The Fire Safety Meeting is a requirement for all breathers who would like to spin fire and/or volunteer for the fire circle on any given night of the festival. There will be one meeting each evening to ensure everyone has an opportunity to attend. You WILL NOT be allowed to spin fire or volunteer without taking the safety course. NO EXCEPTIONS, thank you! During this meeting we will cover all of the fire safety rules and Breathe procedures in place to keep performers, volunteers, and spectators safe. Attendees will be given a crash course regarding regarding how to dress fire-safe, prop maintenance, our fuel depot and circle protocol, active safety, spinning fire, how to safely extinguish props, and emergency situations. Once completed, breathers will be given a wrist band to prove they have taken the course. You must wear your wristband to the circle at night in order to spin. We look forward to cultivating a safe space for fire artists to play and entertain at Breathe.

column19: This workshop will provide approachable, simple, and affordable solutions at a manageable scale. The goal of this workshop is to leave with practical information and feel inspired to make small but sustainable changes. For those new to Zero/Low Waste lifestyle, this discussion will be an opportunity to learn more ways to reduce your carbon footprint. For those who are already active in this lifestyle, there will be time to share what changes you have made, and what challenges you have faced. We will briefly touch on minimalism, buy for life products, DIY, shopping organic, and how these practices can help you reduce your waste.

column18: The Environment: Let's Talk About It
column19: With so much information out there, it can be difficult to know how to even approach the topic of our environment. There are many different opinions about what to care about and how to approach each issue. It is through conversation that we are able to bridge differences and come up with potential solutions. Even those who have a mutual passion for the environment can have different viewpoints, as Margaret and Ashley recently discovered for themselves! Come share in an open discussion about how to bridge these differences and engage in productive conversations about our planet. All viewpoints and opinions are welcome!

column18: Self Care: It’s more than just a massage.
column19: Do you feel like your self care practice is missing something? Do you ever feel worse after engaging in a self care activity? Much of our understanding of self care is centered around feeling pleasure. In this talk Ashley will explore the grittier sides of self care. She will offer some journaling prompts to help expand beyond the conventional definition of self-care. Learn what it means to start creating space for a self care practice that goes beyond the massage!!

column18: Power of Breath - Introduction to Pranayama
column19: Pranayama is the practice of stretching or extending the vital life force inside of us out from the center and through the whole body. Pranayama is more than just breathing techniques; energy follows awareness! Ancient yogic texts tell us that our state of mind is closely linked to the quality of prana within, and because we can influence the flow of prana through the flow of our breath, the quality of our breath influences the state of our mind, and vice versa (Heart of Yoga, T.K.V. Desikachar). After a brief introduction to the topic, this workshop will include both seated practice and simple movements with coordinated breathing. Develop a new appreciation for the power of your breath! Bring Your Own Yoga Mat.

column18: Clothing Swap (and we'll do some educating about the cause)
column19:
Drop off day on the first day of the festival. Every day following, the tent will be open for anyone to pick. Donation bins will be available and clearly marked for those who can't donate on the first day. This will be setup the entire festival.
WHAT: Free clothes for all! No money/currency will be exchanged. Love each other and our precious Gaia, Mother Earth. Give clothes or take clothes. As many as you want or need. If you donate, donate clothes that are still good to wear. All styles, all kinds, cold weather, warm weather, water, snow, deep space, anything is welcome except underwear/socks, just to be safe (unless the underwear/socks have never been worn). Hangers are welcome too.
WHY: We are doing a clothing swap because it's an easy way to show love to one another by sharing abundance, giving and receiving gifts, and helping our planet suffer less. There's an overabundance of clothes on our planet. Buying clothes new or from big stores not only supports large multinational companies who hire underpaid workers in the poorest conditions, but also unnecessarily exerts our nurturing Gaia (our living planet) during production and shipping. Some of us have a closet full of clothes that go unworn while some of us have only a tattered shirt. Give your surplus. Kindly take what you need or want, and don't hesitate to bring/take a lot, this is by you and for you.

column18: Heal the Soil to Heal Our World
column19: This class elucidates the connections between human relationship with the soil, effects associated with climate change, the impact on the water cycle and human health. We will explore the symbiosis between plants and their fungal and bacterial friends which when nurtured create healing in the systems mentioned above, but when destroyed through human industry create some the biggest problems we are facing today. Learn how the water cycle is replenished through taking care of our soil, and how our food can be grown in a regenerative way that heals our health and the health of our ecosystems which are one in the same.

column18: Cultivating an Inclusive Culture. Compromise and Clear Communication
column19: This workshop aims to expose the subtle and often unintentional ways that normative society excludes neurologically or culturally divergent people by sharing their stories. I will personally be sharing my experience as someone with a history of depression, anxiety, and possible undiagnosed Autism. My hope is that these stories will bring to awareness the immense effort that someone from any minority group must apply in order to fit into or even just survive in our society. With this new awareness, we will explore and practice methods of communication and compromise that aim to be inclusive for all. This includes written communication, direct language, and allowing time for someone to respond, as well as unlearning the typical non-verbal signs that someone is connecting and listening. We all have a unique way of existing in this world, so I invite us to step away from the pressure to conform, and to come into this space with an open mind and heart, prepared to see new ways of being that they may never understand, but are willing to accept. Stim toys will be provided! If you are interested in sharing, or would like to speak with me in advance, please email me at anaibriz13@gmail.com

column19: Yoga Nidra led by Rachel Sherron Matrejek with Sound Healing provided by Jade Lyons. Yoga nidra is a state in which the body is completely relaxed, and the practitioner becomes systematically and increasingly aware of the inner world by following a set of verbal instructions. This state of consciousness is different from meditation in which concentration on a single focus is required. In yoga nidra the practitioner remains in a state of light withdrawal of the 5 senses with four senses internalised, that is, withdrawn, and only hearing still connects to any instructions given.

column19: Writing meaningful poetry can be cathartic, but also somewhat intimidating. The block out method allows you to start with pre-existing words on a page. By circling the words you want to use, you string them together into a poem, and then block out the rest. You can also draw or paint over the blocked out words to create an interdisciplinary art piece. Or, just use the process to write a poem! This workshop will teach you how to use this method to write poetry, as well as give you ideas and examples for how to integrate an artistic slant to your poems. Drawing and painting materials will be provided. About the instructor: artist and high school art teacher Mary Palmer has a master's degree in art education, a bachelor's in philosophy and fine art, and is the co-founder of Three Seeds Gallery in Chicago. She enjoys creating community programming and interdisciplinary art projects that incorporate social/emotional learning. This is her third year teaching an art workshop at Breathe.

column18: Haunted Hoop: Introductory and Intermediate Concepts in Two-Handed Hoop Flow
column19: How much can one flow while keeping both hands on a hoop? The answer may be surprising. Participants in this workshop will get to explore basic ways to flow a hoop with both hands on, working into flow movements that embellish the illusion of both hands controlling the flow of the hoop. This includes ghosting, isolations, and more illusion flow! Some hoops can be provided, but it is recommended that participants in this workshop bring a moderate to smaller sized hoop without wicks to use.

column19:
Zero-Point Meditation: 15 years of dedicated practice of mindfulness meditation guided the Refusionist to Remembering... Zero-Point Meditation is a technique that aims to help one become physically aware of the connection point between our physical experience and the co-creative dream that is reality. We are all born of an infinite wisdom that is buried deep within a quantum tapestry woven with threads of DNA and Life Experience. When we prime our focus towards re-discovering the physical connection between one's body and consciousness, we forge a neurological bridge of physical presence that is deepened and strengthened the longer and more often one returns to their practice of mindfulness. In meditating together, we create a space of support while venturing deep into one's own oneness. As this daily practice is meant to build upon itself, the Refusionist will teach the technique before each meditation while offering other helpful tools for cultivating mindfulness.
Join in on the experience of learning this technique, meditating together, and learning from each other's unique perspectives. For while it is Impossible to Know All, it IS possible to Know Of the All and accelerate our knowing by learning via the connections we may build and open to together.

Zero-Point Meditation: 15 years of dedicated practice of mindfulness meditation guided the Refusionist to Remembering... Zero-Point Meditation is a technique that aims to help one become physically aware of the connection point between our physical experience and the co-creative dream that is reality. We are all born of an infinite wisdom that is buried deep within a quantum tapestry woven with threads of DNA and Life Experience. When we prime our focus towards re-discovering the physical connection between one's body and consciousness, we forge a neurological bridge of physical presence that is deepened and strengthened the longer and more often one returns to their practice of mindfulness. In meditating together, we create a space of support while venturing deep into one's own oneness. As this daily practice is meant to build upon itself, the Refusionist will teach the technique before each meditation while offering other helpful tools for cultivating mindfulness.
Join in on the experience of learning this technique, meditating together, and learning from each other's unique perspectives. For while it is Impossible to Know All, it IS possible to Know Of the All and accelerate our knowing by learning via the connections we may build and open to together.

column18: Getting Twisted: wire wrap pendant and single stone setting
column19: In this workshop students will learn how to construct a one of a kind wire wrap pendant. They will learn about the metal and its malleability. Learn how to construct a bail and how to set a stone: applicable to cabochons, faceted crystals, and natural formed crystals. Students are encouraged to bring their own stone, as well as pliers and wire cutters if possible. Also feel free to bring your own wire if you have it! A stone and copper wire to wrap will be provided for those who need it. A limited supply of pliers and wire cutters will be available to share as needed. By the end of the class, students will walk out with a creation of their own and the knowledge to boot!

Workshop instructor Sailor Cari will be posted up on thursday while attendees arrive, and before the workshop with a sign-up sheet. First come first serve.

column18: Acroyoga Super Stars! Working with ALL the Side Stars, Stars, and Reverse Stars
column19: Be an acro super star! Stars and side stars are critical poses in building a solid acroyoga practice. We will work our way through all sorts of star poses and transitions with an emphasis on stability and increasing control in movement. This workshop is great if you want to step up your acro practice. We will start with strengthening some core star poses including side star and star. If we find success with static poses we will work some transitionary movements between different types of stars. Finally, for those who want a challenge, we will play with some more complicated balances, including mono-balances and goofy stars. This workshop is good for beginners who have some previous experience with acroyoga, or intermediate acroyogis who wish to improve their form and challenge their balance in more advanced variations of star, a key pose in any acro practice. Prerequisite: some experience with side star and star, enthusiasm for acrobatic yoga, willingness to challenge yourself and play with new friends

Bring mats and water.

Pre-req: cartwheels, bird, star, and strong spotting.

column18: Intuitive Eating: Discovering What Your Body Needs To Flourish
column19: Today we see a lot of different dietary trends going around and products that support these types of diets. Keto, Paleo, Intermittent Fasting, Vegan, but not many people realize that there is no "one diet fits all". We are all bio-individual, and what food may be healing for some, may be harmful to another. In this workshop, I go over the common diets you see today and help you discover which foods work best for your individual body to feel the most nourished. I also talk about how the power of healing through food has changed my life and helped with my autoimmune issues as well as reversing symptoms and certain health conditions. Intuitive eating to me is feeling connected to what you're eating and using food as fuel, the way it was intended to.

column18: Bowspring--The Evolution of Yoga: A Posture and Movement Practice for the New Millennium
column19: Discover the Bowspring, the new posture of human evolution. Freedom, courage, and superhuman strength can be yours by inserting this 10 part postural template into your ordinary daily activities and your athletic endeavors. Enjoy a Bowspring Flow, derived from, yet vastly different from modern postural yoga. Some of the benefits of this practice are open mind, courage, confidence, whittled waist, and lifted booty. Power, pleasure, primal movement medicine... discover why people worldwide are so in love with Bowspring! Feel the results and learn why the benefits happen so quickly with practice: increased muscle mass, strength, and grace in all activities! This isn't just a practice on the mat, this is a proven system that enhances every single action you do with your body throughout the day... improve your game in sports, increase your ability in dance, or any other movement of choice. Remove pain from your life. Empower yourself and have fun while doing it!

column18: So You Think You Can't Acro? The Basics!
column19: Acro is so much fun, just knowing a few moves can help you relax, meet new folks, build strength, and get comfy in your body. This workshop will be an intro to Acro yoga. Moving through prep work, leaning the basics, and doing a little flying! If you are new to basing or flying this is the class for you! If you want a re-fresh or have flown but would like to base - join us! It's going to be fun! Sophia and Josh have been doing Acro yoga for a little over a year. Sophia is a RYT 200hr and has been teaching yoga for over 10 years. In Acro they both found a new way to connect to self, others, and increase strength and relaxation. Come join the fun of Acro! Please bring a yoga mat or blanket.

Feel free to OPT OUT of the hands on adjustments from the teacher, Breathe is YOUR experience. No partner necessary- this is just an option!

column19: Join BREATHE's first edition of the BREATHE run club. Come get your run in before the Midwestern humidity sets in and start your day off on the right foot! Meet at the front gate to join the group as we take the long way around to the back pond, where we'll end the run with a stretch and short meditation before hiking back to the campgrounds together. The run is just under four miles - all abilities are welcome (especially beginners!!), this run will be treated as a "no drop" run. Start together, finish together!

column19: Shibari is the art of Japanese rope bondage. In this workshop, we'll explore shibari as a partnered movement art, focusing on how to connect and communicate through rope. To get the most out of this class, it is recommended to attend with a partner you are comfortable touching and being in close physical proximity with. Wear something that is easy to move around in, such as yoga clothing. Natural fiber rope will be available to borrow or purchase if don't have your own. This session will be open only to those who are 19 or older.

column19: Shibari is the art of Japanese rope bondage. This workshop will focus on two of the most important ties of traditional shibari: the single column and the futomomo. The single column is one of the core building blocks of shibari. The futomomo is a classic leg tie with a wide variety of applications. Everything in this class can be tied on one's self, so participants are welcome to work individually or with a partner. Natural fiber rope will be available to borrow or purchase if you don't have your own. This session will be open only to those who are 19 or older.

column18: The Art of Playing with Clay
column19: Join Jac for an open conversation about the benefits of applying clay to your skin [YOUR LARGEST ORGAN] And then playtime! Feel free to come by yourself or bring a partner to help with the application. All product will be provided. Organic, Vegan, Gluten Free, Paleo and Whole 30 Friendly ha ha ha. All ages, humans, and pets invited. Please bring a towel. And let's get DIRTY!

column18: Slackline Inversions: Using your Legs like Arms
column19: Are you looking for new ways to play on a slackline? Have you ever considered, maybe, using your legs like arms? Slackline supported inversions are rad way to have fun on a line and find a new perspective. In this short workshop, we'll explore playful ways to get upside-down on a slackline, building the basics towards a hands-free shoulder stand. All levels welcome!

column19: In the first half, we are going to spark discussion and create movement within our bodies, minds, and perspectives. How do we cultivate a constant container, in multiple/all aspects of our lives, in which free expression is encouraged? How do we best enable each other to interact and collaborate in honest ways? As we are constantly evolving, as humans always do, how do we use expression as a tool in that (co)evolution? The second half will involve live musicians who will improvise music that is inspired by the movements of the dancers, and the dancers will move in ways inspired by the music (positive feed back kinda thing). The vision includes at least one guitar player and one hand drum player to lead the sound, sitting on the ground at the same level as everyone else. Maracas and tambourines for the workshop attendees for a more inclusive feel. Free movement from the bodies AND the sound waves. In full, we'll dance, sing, and discuss with open minds about all different ways to purely, truthfully, and lovingly express in this human existence!

column19: Shiatsu translates roughly into finger pressure. This workshop will be a partnered class (feel free to come un-partnered, and we will team people up!) In this workshop you will learn to give a balanced, soothing, and relaxing full body shiatsu massage using slow rhythmic pressure along meridians and Ayurvedic longlines. Shiatsu promotes energy flow, health, wellness, and relaxation! I will go over a brief energy pattern in the class, and emphasize the proper flow throughout our time in order to facilitate balance within the mind and body. Touch is so incredibly important, and I am excited to share this form of touch and healing with the community! *Please bring yoga mats, or blankets to lay on, and a pillow if you're feeling it.

column19: Allow yourself to melt into the space of receiving. We will lead you through a yin yoga practice infused with Reiki to create space for healing in the physical body, energetic body, mind, and soul. In Yin Yoga, we hold poses for several minutes to allow the muscles to relax for opening in the joints, ligaments, and energetic body. Reiki is a form of hands on healing where energies from the universe are pulled up through the body and transmitted down through the hands of the Reiki Master and placed into the body of the recipient.

column19: Contact Improvisation is a free-form improvisational dance performed with at least one partner but can also be done with 3+ people. We will play games that help us become more comfortable with engaging in movement with another person, followed by games and exercises that help us learn how to obtain consent non-verbally and how to safely share weight in dance.

column19: An exploration into contact improv. This workshop will explore what it means to connect with others through improvisational movement. Using unique exercises and guided games, participants will create new shapes, find flow, and learn how to move with each other by sharing weight. They will investigate the possibilities of movement while pushing their comfort and trust boundaries in space with other people. No partner necessary.

column18: This is How to Tie a "Sliding X", Prove me Wrong: An interactive knot tying workshop
column19: Used to distribute a load evenly across multiple anchor points the infamous "Sliding X" is one of the most crucial tools in the belt of any aspiring highline rigger. After 7 years of highline rigging I've had many concerning conversations with highliners about this knot. I've also seen many experienced highline riggers unknowly tie this knot inorrectly due to lack of proper inspection techniques. This workshop is intended for slackliners of all skill levels. Attendees will have the opportunity to get hands on learning on how to tie a Sliding X and how to ensure any given Sliding X is tied properly. This workshop is a safe place for anyone to share and discuss their opinions, knowledge, and questions on the Sliding X. *Bring your yoga mat or a comfy chair if you please! All other materials provided.

column18: Weaving the Web of Your Mind
column19: *BRING YOUR JOURNAL* Are you able to give your goals undivided attention and feel confident facing your deepest insecurities and doubts to pursue your purpose? This isn't your TEDtalk. Are you looking for a supportive approach and tools for diving into your Shadow Work? The work of dealing with tough feelings, hard transitions, or overwhelming realizations is never hopeless, although it can seem like a confusing and sticky mess of dead bugs. In this guided journal and meditation discussion, we'll clear out the old cob webs, weave new patterns of thinking to stick to your true intentions and capture your goals. You'll leave with words to look back on when you're weathering your future storms.

column18: Creating from the Center: Mandala Workshop
column19: Join Visionary Artist Ryan Blume as he guides us through the process of the meditative art of Mandalas. Starting from the center, our shared eternal soul essence, we will move outward in concentric circles, creating and expressing our unique selves in shape and color. No experience needed, as guidance will be provided on a group and individual level as needed. Each participant will leave with their mandala creation as an embodiment of their unique expression and artifact of their workshop experience that can help them recreate more mandalas on their own. This workshop is suitable for all ages.

column18: The Posterior Chain- Yoga for low back pain

Giving you new variations to put in your yoga tool belt and some of my favorite ways to relieve low back pain. All levels are welcome!
